\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {15}{\ignorespaces The human semantics $\sigma _H$ as learned. Rules 1--3 are near-textbook --- jointly, a \emph  {committal} complete-like policy with cycle handling, though rule 1's escape clause tolerates conflict among accepted arguments (see the principle profile below). Rule 4 is a \emph  {candidate} hedge: psychologically suggestive --- graded and ranking-based semantics posit exactly this attack-load sensitivity axiomatically~\citep  {grossi2019graded,amgoud2013ranking,bonzon2016ranking} --- but it recurs in only $5$ of $20$ cross-seed folds and its antecedent is realized exactly once in the corpus (see text).}}{45}{figure.15}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:humansem}{{15}{45}{The human semantics $\sigma _H$ as learned. Rules 1--3 are near-textbook --- jointly, a \emph {committal} complete-like policy with cycle handling, though rule 1's escape clause tolerates conflict among accepted arguments (see the principle profile below). Rule 4 is a \emph {candidate} hedge: psychologically suggestive --- graded and ranking-based semantics posit exactly this attack-load sensitivity axiomatically~\citep {grossi2019graded,amgoud2013ranking,bonzon2016ranking} --- but it recurs in only $5$ of $20$ cross-seed folds and its antecedent is realized exactly once in the corpus (see text)}{figure.15}{}}
