\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {17}{\ignorespaces Two decision trees learned agnostically from structure (clean labels, fold~1), shown after collapsing constant subtrees. \textbf  {(a)}~Grounded: three legible rules approximating grounded acceptance (reachability from the unattacked core, minus direct undefended attack), the target feature learners fit best. \textbf  {(b)}~Credulous-stable: one clean rule, then a tangle of $\sim $20 splits whose leaves mix \textsf  {in}/\textsf  {out} with no coherent rule --- credulous stable acceptance is a global property of the extension \emph  {set} that local features cannot capture. Grounded is functional (one extension), so a local heuristic gets close; stable is multi-extension, so it does not.}}{56}{figure.17}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:learned_trees}{{17}{56}{Two decision trees learned agnostically from structure (clean labels, fold~1), shown after collapsing constant subtrees. \textbf {(a)}~Grounded: three legible rules approximating grounded acceptance (reachability from the unattacked core, minus direct undefended attack), the target feature learners fit best. \textbf {(b)}~Credulous-stable: one clean rule, then a tangle of $\sim $20 splits whose leaves mix \pred {in}/\pred {out} with no coherent rule --- credulous stable acceptance is a global property of the extension \emph {set} that local features cannot capture. Grounded is functional (one extension), so a local heuristic gets close; stable is multi-extension, so it does not}{figure.17}{}}
